text: I would say they move around all of the time, but over different cycle frequencies, depending on the opportunity or exposure. So there might be some places, I gave the example of, say, for example, long volatility and large cap energy companies versus short volatility and smaller energy companies. Those type of things typically would be an opportunity at a point in time that might show up driven by a series of large transactions in the equity market where, for example, a large fund was doing a bunch of overriding in their large cap energy names, which suddenly made them very cheap. That might be the kind of thing that shows up from time to time and you really have to monitor and understand what's going on and see the prices move and understand why. There are other dislocations and other relative value opportunities that might suck. over time, but be much stickier in passing. So we'll talk in a little bit more detail about some of the types of things that large pension funds do in the equity options market. But over the last several years, there's been a very substantial growth in index call overriding and index cash secured put selling among pension funds trying to generate income relative to their equity portfolios. And that's creating some certain types of opportunities. And I think there's a lot of opportunity that might last for several years while those strategies are popular. And then you can imagine it becoming too popular and over some number of years, then the pendulum swinging the other way. So I think there's a spectrum of the time cycle. I wouldn't say that there are many risk premia that you would expect in the space to just exist in perpetuity in a relative value sense.
